revision.text:
The '''Arlesey Bomb''' is an [[angling weight]] developed by [[Richard Walker (angler)|Richard Walker]] at the lake in [[Arlesey]]. Walker fished for [[perch]] in the lake, and very large perch could be caught in the deepest water. The Arlesey Bomb was developed to allow him to cast the long distances required.<ref>{{cite book|title= Catfish|series= Successful Angling|author= Maddocks, Kevin|year=2005|publisher= Coch-y-Bonddu Books|page= 46|isbn= 9781904784098}}</ref> It is tear-shaped, with a loop at the top to attach the line. Its shape makes it [[Aerodynamics|aerodynamic]] to cast, but unlikely to snag on the river or lake bottom. The incorporation of a swivel also prevented the line getting twisted.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Fred Buller's Book of Rigs & Tackles|last = Buller|first = Fred|publisher = Paulton House|year = 1967|location = London|pages = 11}}</ref>

