{{Infobox company | name = GF Biochemicals | logo = | image = | image_caption = | type = | traded_as = | foundation = | location = | key_people = [[Mathieu Flamini]], Pasquale Granata | num_employees = 400<ref name=BBC /> | industry = | products = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | assets = | equity = | homepage = {{url|www.gfbiochemicals.com/}} }}
'''GF Biochemicals''' is a biochemical company founded in 2008. It was co-founded by and named after [[Mathieu Flamini]] and Pasquale Granata. It is the first company in the world able to mass-produce [[levulinic acid]].<ref name="mirror">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/arsenal-star-mathieu-flamini-reveals-6831238|title=Arsenal star Mathieu Flamini reveals secret he has been keeping from team-mates for SEVEN years - Mirror Online|publisher=mirror.co.uk|accessdate=2016-05-05|date=2015-11-14}}</ref> The company worked with the [[University of Pisa]] for seven years on its production.<ref name="BBC">{{cite web|author1=Tim Bowler|author2=Russell Hotten|title=Mathieu Flamini: Arsenal's biochemical midfielder|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-36037874|website=BBC News|accessdate=2016-05-05|date=2016-04-15}}</ref> In 2016 GF Biochemicals acquired the American company Segetis.<ref name="dailymail">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3506132/Mathieu-Flamini-s-business-GF-Biochemicals-acquires-company-Segetis-savvy-Arsenal-midfielder-continues-look-green-alternatives-oil.html|title=Arsenal star Mathieu Flamini's business GF Biochemicals acquires Segetis &#124; Daily Mail Online|publisher=dailymail.co.uk|accessdate=2016-05-05|date=2016-03-23|author=John Downes}}</ref> The company has a plant in [[Caserta]] that employs around 80 people.<ref name="thesun">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/football/6742052/Mathieu-Flaminis-no-fuel.html|title=Mathieu Flamini's no fuel|publisher=thesun.co.uk|accessdate=2016-05-05|date=2015-11-13|author=Antony Kastrinakis}}</ref> In 2015, the company won the John Sime Award for Most Innovative New Technology.<ref>{{cite web|title=GFBiochemicals Wins John Sime Award for Most Innovative New Technology|url=http://www.bioplasticsmagazine.com/en/news/meldungen/20151030-GF-wins-award.php|website=bioplasticsmagazine.com|accessdate=2016-05-05|date=2015-10-30}}</ref> The company has offices in [[Milan]] and the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=BBC />
